<subSubSection id="C33E6525FF92FFC364B3FDBF5AC8FBE8" pageId="10" pageNumber="192" type="description">
<paragraph id="8B9B36AEFF92FFC364B3FDBF587EF8EC" blockId="10.[151,1437,1467,2034]" box="[151,351,1467,1493]" pageId="10" pageNumber="192">DESCRIPTION:</paragraph>
<paragraph id="8B9B36AEFF92FFC364E3FDE458E7F8C3" blockId="10.[151,1437,1467,2034]" box="[199,454,1503,1530]" pageId="10" pageNumber="192">
<emphasis id="B950EABCFF92FFC364E3FDE45875F8C0" box="[199,340,1503,1529]" italics="true" pageId="10" pageNumber="192">Wing length</emphasis>
: 5.0 mm.
</paragraph>
<paragraph id="8B9B36AEFF92FFC364E3FE005BAFFB78" blockId="10.[151,1437,1467,2034]" pageId="10" pageNumber="192">
<emphasis id="B950EABCFF92FFC364E3FE005827FB24" box="[199,262,1540,1565]" italics="true" pageId="10" pageNumber="192">Wing</emphasis>
(
<figureCitation id="131F2A2BFF92FFC36532FE07585EFB24" box="[278,383,1539,1565]" captionStart="FIGURE 10" captionStartId="11.[151,264,829,853]" captionTargetBox="[160,1428,248,800]" captionTargetId="figure-52@11.[152,1436,237,806]" captionTargetPageId="11" captionText="FIGURE 10. Anopheles ziemanni: a, wing; b, hindleg (from Gillies &amp; de Meillon 1968)." figureDoi="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.6521626" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/6521626/files/figure.png" pageId="10" pageNumber="192">Fig. 10a</figureCitation>
): Subcostal and preapical pale spots present; pale fringe spot at apex of wing extending from R 
<subScript id="17A034EBFF92FFC364CBFE3E59D9FB71" attach="left" box="[239,248,1594,1608]" fontSize="6" pageId="10" pageNumber="192">2</subScript>
to R 
<subScript id="17A034EBFF92FFC36510FE3D5871FB7E" attach="left" box="[308,336,1593,1607]" fontSize="6" pageId="10" pageNumber="192">4+5</subScript>
, similar to 
<emphasis id="B950EABCFF92FFC365F9FE235BAFFB78" box="[477,654,1575,1601]" italics="true" pageId="10" pageNumber="192">
<taxonomicName id="4C244D2DFF92FFC365F9FE235BABFB78" authorityName="van Someren" authorityYear="1947" box="[477,650,1575,1601]" class="Insecta" family="Culicidae" genus="Anopheles" kingdom="Animalia" order="Diptera" pageId="10" pageNumber="192" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="fuscicolor">An. fuscicolor</taxonomicName>
.
</emphasis>
</paragraph>
<paragraph id="8B9B36AEFF92FFC364E3FE4F5A2EFB5C" blockId="10.[151,1437,1467,2034]" box="[199,783,1611,1638]" pageId="10" pageNumber="192">
<emphasis id="B950EABCFF92FFC364E3FE4F58B1FB5C" box="[199,400,1611,1637]" italics="true" pageId="10" pageNumber="192">Maxillary palpus</emphasis>
: Shaggy, with four pale bands.
</paragraph>
<paragraph id="8B9B36AEFF92FFC364E3FE745AC8FBE8" blockId="10.[151,1437,1467,2034]" pageId="10" pageNumber="192">
<emphasis id="B950EABCFF92FFC364E3FE745820FBB0" box="[199,257,1648,1673]" italics="true" pageId="10" pageNumber="192">Legs</emphasis>
(
<figureCitation id="131F2A2BFF92FFC36536FE6B585FFBB3" box="[274,382,1647,1674]" captionStart="FIGURE 10" captionStartId="11.[151,264,829,853]" captionTargetBox="[160,1428,248,800]" captionTargetId="figure-52@11.[152,1436,237,806]" captionTargetPageId="11" captionText="FIGURE 10. Anopheles ziemanni: a, wing; b, hindleg (from Gillies &amp; de Meillon 1968)." figureDoi="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.6521626" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/6521626/files/figure.png" pageId="10" pageNumber="192">Fig. 10b</figureCitation>
): Apex of foretibia and base of foretarsomere 1 always dark. Apex of hindtibia, base of hindtarsomere 1 and apices of hindtarsomeres 2 and 3 with pale spots at most 3 times as wide as diameter of the tarsomere; hindtarsomeres 4 and 5 pale, 0.5 of hindtarsomere 3 pale.
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
<subSubSection id="C33E6525FF92FFC364E3FEDF5BCCFAC8" pageId="10" pageNumber="192" type="biology_ecology">
<paragraph id="8B9B36AEFF92FFC364E3FEDF5D02FA20" blockId="10.[151,1437,1467,2034]" pageId="10" pageNumber="192">LARVAL HABITAT: Natural collections of clear water with aquatic and semi-aquatic vegetation, such as swamps, ponds, backwaters of streams, springs, ditches and rice fields.</paragraph>
<paragraph id="8B9B36AEFF92FFC364E3FF275BCCFAC8" blockId="10.[151,1437,1467,2034]" pageId="10" pageNumber="192">
ADULT BIOLOGY: Collections of 
<taxonomicName id="4C244D2DFF92FFC3667FFF275BCFFA04" authorityName="Grunberg" authorityYear="1902" box="[603,750,1827,1853]" class="Insecta" family="Culicidae" genus="Anopheles" kingdom="Animalia" order="Diptera" pageId="10" pageNumber="192" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="ziemanni">
<emphasis id="B950EABCFF92FFC3667FFF275BCFFA04" box="[603,750,1827,1853]" italics="true" pageId="10" pageNumber="192">An. ziemanni</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
tested for infections of 
<taxonomicName id="4C244D2DFF92FFC367DFFF205DB3FA04" box="[1019,1170,1827,1853]" family="Plasmodiidae" genus="Plasmodium" kingdom="Chromista" order="Eucoccidiida" pageId="10" pageNumber="192" phylum="Miozoa" rank="species" species="falciparum">
<emphasis id="B950EABCFF92FFC367DFFF205DB3FA04" box="[1019,1170,1827,1853]" italics="true" pageId="10" pageNumber="192">P. falciparum</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
showed positivity rates of 0.3–2.9% in 
<collectingCountry id="F333763EFF92FFC3656EFF43589EFA58" box="[330,447,1863,1889]" name="Cameroon" pageId="10" pageNumber="192">Cameroon</collectingCountry>
(
<bibRefCitation id="EFB54B5FFF92FFC365F4FF435A25FA58" author="Gillies, M. T. &amp; de Meillon, B." box="[464,772,1863,1889]" pageId="10" pageNumber="192" pagination="1 - 343" refId="ref8483" refString="Gillies, M. T. &amp; de Meillon, B. (1968) The Anophelinae of Africa south of the Sahara (Ethiopian Zoogeographical Region). Publications of the South African Institute for Medical Research, 54, 1 - 343." type="journal article" year="1968">Gillies &amp; de Meillon 1968</bibRefCitation>
